Mystery solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. This was found by scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Progress has also been made on the question of why children defend themselves so fiercely against tickling, only to demand more.
Finally, it was also shown why the approach of a tickling hand alone triggers laughter even before touch. This is due to a low-lying layer in the cerebrium, which already triggers the laughter in the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, previous research showed that rats react with "laughter" in the ultrasound range when they are tickled by humans. This "laughter" is conveyed by the part of the cerebral cortex, which serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touching
Until now, it had been assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - so people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers now found in the experiments on the rats that the laughter as well as the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during a self-touch. This is also the case when living beings clean themselves. During the foreign contact and the tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh were amplified.
But if the self-touch and the touch by others happen at the same time, laughter is also suppressed. This indicates that the rat’s brain cannot distinguish between self-touching and touch by others. The new findings suggested that people cannot tickle themselves because self-touching activates a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. In the process, they sometimes prematurely broke off this initiation in the experiment, showing flight behavior or stare. This ambivalence is similar to the behavior of the children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral reaction that is the same in rats and people.
