Attention: NIE wireless charging
Practical but harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently come on the market, which support wireless charging and sell very well - above all the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July. The wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature increases battery
Researchers warn of wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the University of Warwick, this is extremely harmful to the devices. The reason for this is the significantly larger heat development. If you charge a mobile phone normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. In the case of wireless charging, however, the researchers have always measured above 30 degrees even with the perfect orientation of the smartphone on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is slightly next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage of the charging pad also increases, which in turn increases the power consumption.
Capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, the temperature for the durability of batteries is a crucial factor. Every single degree plays a role. When charging with higher temperatures, the battery not only rebounds in capacity, but it also does not last so long overall. The service life is therefore lower. The researchers therefore advise to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since battery replacement is always associated with high costs for modern smartphones, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has recently increased the cost of a battery replacement even again - and for all iPhones.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: Simply put the device on a corresponding charging pad - these are now even installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without annoying cable salad and arduous plug fumble. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy transmission) is a worldwide standard, in which, for once, even Apple participates, there are hardly any restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should only be applied in exceptional cases.
