The said body was discovered by an amateur astronomer named Gennadi Borissov in Crimea. He looked up at the sky with a self-built telescope and further follow-up confirmed his first suspicion. It is actually an unknown comet that does not originate from our solar system. He is only the second of its kind to be spotted while passing through.
The great opportunity for astronomers now is to catch glimpses of an alien solar system from close range. Apparently, the Come is similar to those of our own system, as the astrophysical institute of the Canary Islands reports. According to the International Astronomical Union (IAC), the comet is of a clear interstellar origin and is currently operating on a so-called hyperbolar, which leads it out of our system.
Comet has already been spotted before approach - and can be observed for several months
But before that happens, astronomers can observe it in depth. Because unlike his predecessor, 2I/Borisov has already been sighted in his approach, which means that he can be studied from Earth for many months. "The object will reach the greatest brightness in mid-December and then be visible with medium-sized telescopes until April 2020," explains Davide Farnocchia of the US space agency Nasa. "After that, it will only be possible to observe with larger, professional telescopes until October 2020."
The new visitor's predecessor: 1I/2017 U1 "Oumuamua".
First findings about Comet 2I/Borisov raise hopes in science
According to the first findings, the comet is estimated to be 2 to 16 kilometers in diameter. At the same time, the celestial body seems similar to our comet - because as IAC researcher Julia de León puts it, the spectrum of the tail star is similar to ours. This observation suggests that comets in other solar systems could be formed by processes similar to those in ours, added de León’s colleague Javier Licandro.
