Aegean: Baby and four other children drown in boat accident
When capsizing a refugee boat in the Aegean Sea, a baby and four other children drowned. In total, seven people died in the accident, the Greek coast guard announced on Friday. Nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men were rescued.
Currently, hundreds of migrants from Turkey are transferring to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean Sea. Last year, 174 people died on this route, according to the United Nations Refugee Agency (UNHCR). Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer has now announced that he intends to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the responsible EU commissioner, he wanted to "inform himself in Turkey about what the refugee situation is like," Seehofer said on Friday. He then wanted to learn more about the "administrative problems of the Greeks" in Athens in order to be able to help cope.
A spokeswoman for the EU Commission confirmed Seehofer's planned trip on Friday with EU Interior Commissioner Dimitris Avramopoulos and France's Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
In Greece, an unusual number of migrants continue to arrive from Turkey. On Tuesday alone, 654 people moved to the Greek islands, the Greek civil protection ministry said on Wednesday.
Is the Turkey deal still working?
The increased figures recently raised doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey agreement concluded in 2016. This provides that the EU can send back all refugees and migrants who come to the Greek islands illegally via Turkey. In return, the EU wanted to take in a Syrian refugee from Turkey for every deported Syrian.
However, the processing of asylum applications is progressing only laboriously on the Greek side due to a lack of staff. Lesbos, Chios, Samos, Leros and Kos are waiting for almost 29 400 people, according to the Ministry of Civil Protection. The worst is the situation on Lesbos: in a camp with capacity for 650 people, 5200 migrants are currently housed.
Never since the EU-Turkey Refugee Pact came into force in March 2016 have there been so many, the state broadcaster reported.
