Influencer wants free upgrade: Lifetime flight ban at Cathay
Jaqueline Ng was allegedly assured of an upgrade by email from Cathay Pacific. But when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed to board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Spontaneously getting an upgrade for business class - many passengers dream of it. Sometimes they are lucky, and the employees at check-in offer a change from economy class for free.
However, this case shows how not to do it: A self-declared influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. On Instagram, Jaqueline Ng is followed by more than 65,000 users. On 30. It is May from Taiwan to New York and on 7. June flown back.
On the outbound flight, employees refused to upgrade Jaqueline, despite showing a mail in which her Cathay Pacific allegedly offered an upgrade. The letter is said to have been received by the influencer from a marketing employee of the airline. The airline, on the other hand, accuses Jaqueline of forging the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have presented the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK Airport were skeptical: they checked at the headquarters. And in fact, the employee from whom the mail allegedly came is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system in which the messages did not appear.
Airline staff at the airport canceled Jaquelines Ticket and imposed a lifetime flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For 1,400 US dollars (around 1,280 euros) she had to buy a new flight ticket to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests. Because Cathay had reimbursed her the price for her original ticket, but Jaqueline also demanded the cost of the new ticket back.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: For Cathay, the influencer has committed fraud, she remains blocked for future flights. The airline’s terms and conditions also state that it does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline doesn't want to settle for that - and is now turning on a lawyer.
Oil prices give in after Yemen ceasefire report
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar on Friday noon within a very short time. Most recently, a barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - around 1.4 percent less than the previous day. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
The trigger for the price slide was a report by the Wall Street Journal about a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone strike on the oil facilities in Saudi Arabia had brought five percent of the world's oil production to a halt in mid-September. The Houthi rebels allied with Iran in the civil war-torn country of Yemen had claimed the attacks for themselves. Saudi Arabia, like the U.S. government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse political tension in the region.
Should an agreement actually come about, one could focus on growth and demand worries, Ole Hansen, head of the commodity strategy department at Saxo Bank told the Bloomberg news agency.
Oil prices are thus continuing their downward movement of the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had still cost up to nearly 59 dollars, Brent nearly 65 dollars.
Most recently, Bloomberg had reported, citing insiders, that repair work on oil facilities in Saudi Arabia is progressing faster than thought after the attack in mid-September. Accordingly, the production volume has again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original quantity.
Recently, there have been several press releases, citing insiders, who report on rapid progress of the state-owned oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some relaxation in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: The British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is more than two months after the arrest by Iran and the recently granted release on the way to leave the port. The crew is now preparing the departure while the ship is still at anchor, shipping company chief Erik Hånell told Swedish radio in a text message on Friday morning.
However, the U.S. announced that it would move defense missiles and soldiers to the Iranian arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fears of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and Britain had at times significantly driven up oil prices in recent weeks.
