Doping: Further Russian manipulations proven
Material from the Moscow analysis laboratory is manipulated - this is confirmed by David Howman, former director of the World Anti-Doping Agency (Wada) and today's head of integrity of the World Athletics Federation.
At the start of the World Athletics Championships, new details of the doping scandal in Russia come to the fore - and they destroy the little credibility that Russian sport had regained at the beginning of the year and even partially. In January 2019, the Moscow Doping Laboratory finally delivered the required samples from 2012 to 2015 to the World Antidoping Agency (Wada). It turned out they were faked.
In December 2014, systematic fraud was revealed in Russian sport. The Wada had blocked the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (Rusada) for three years. During this time, Russian athletes were not completely banned from the world stage. After individual examination at the 2016 Summer Games in Rio, the International Olympic Committee had around 270 athletes in the country competing under a neutral flag, and 168 Russian athletes competed at the Winter Games in February 2018. They were also allowed to attend the World Cups in the various sports, in the summer even the World Cup with the host took place in Russia as a participant.
Lack of positive findings
The following September, the Wada lifted the Rusada ban again, but demanded access to the laboratory and the said samples. The data should provide information on the extent of the cover-up of doping cases in state doping. They should help to punish athletes retrospectively. Three months later, they were finally delivered.
However, the chairman of the independent Integrity Commission (AIU) of the World Athletics Federation (IAAF) has now confirmed that the doping data from the Moscow analysis laboratory has been manipulated. "Yeah. We received the data nine months ago. We should check whether the task force has received the right data," David Howman told the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper in an interview on Friday. “We have identified numerous discrepancies between the data that Wada received from a whistleblower and the ones she received from the Russians in January.” Many positive findings were missing, which had been mentioned in the McLaren report.
The World Cup not affected
This confirms the IAAF's stance: The Athletics Federation is the only organization to hold on to the ban of Russia. At the World Cup in Doha, 30 Russian athletes start under a neutral flag. They had to prove that they were training outside the Russian system and undergoing tests.
Earlier this week, Wada had already put manipulations in the room, urging Russia to respond to the allegations within three weeks. Russia is now threatening the renewed suspension of the Rusada and, in the worst case, also the exclusion from the 2020 Tokyo Olympics.
